<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="1" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD BGCOLOR="#b6e3b6" WIDTH="150"><B>Rule</B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD ALIGN="left" WIDTH="150">Undoubtedly the words within the<BR ALIGN='left'/>parenthesis of § 203(h) (1) expand the<BR ALIGN='left'/>meaning of &quot;merger&quot; or &quot;consolidation&quot;<BR ALIGN='left'/>to include certain transactions which<BR ALIGN='left'/>partake of the nature of a merger or<BR ALIGN='left'/>consolidation, but are beyond the<BR ALIGN='left'/>ordinary and commonly accepted meaning<BR ALIGN='left'/>of those words. Pinellas Ice &amp; Cold<BR ALIGN='left'/>Storage Co. v. Commissioner, 287 U.S.<BR ALIGN='left'/>462, 53 S.Ct. 257, 77 L.Ed. 428. This is<BR ALIGN='left'/>not to say, however, that the uniting of<BR ALIGN='left'/>business interests is always of a<BR ALIGN='left'/>sufficient nature to qualify as a<BR ALIGN='left'/>nontaxable reorganization.</TD></TR>
